@node Overview "Neptune Documentation - Overview"


   @{b}Overview@{ub}


   @{fg shine}Neptune@{fg text} is an Astrology Program for the Amiga.

   The DEMO Version is freely distributed in the following @{b}Lha archive@{ub}:


   @{fg shine}Nept10.lha@{fg text} (106912 bytes) which contains:


   neptune1.0/docs/Neptune1.0.guide

   neptune1.0/docs/Neptune1.0.guide.info

   neptune1.0/fonts/nami.font

   neptune1.0/fonts/nami/7

   neptune1.0/Install Neptune

   neptune1.0/libs/HBasic2.library

   neptune1.0/rt_ReqDevice

   neptune1.0/Docs.info

   neptune1.0/icons/ni/Docs.info

   neptune1.0/icons/ni/Neptune.info

   neptune1.0/icons/ni/Neptune1.0.guide.info

   neptune1.0/Install Neptune.info

   neptune1.0/Uninstall Neptune.info

   neptune1.0/bin/Neptune1.0

   neptune1.0/icons/mwb/Docs.info

   neptune1.0/icons/mwb/Neptune.info

   neptune1.0/icons/mwb/Neptune1.0.guide.info

   neptune1.0/icons/mwb/Neptune1.0.info

   neptune1.0/icons/ni/Neptune1.0.info

   Neptune1.0.info

   neptune1.0/Uninstall Neptune


   @{fg fill}NOTE:@{fg text}

   If one or more files are missing or have a different length, please
 consider this archive @{i}corrupted@{ui} and download the original from
 @{b}Aminet@{ub} (directory @{b}misc/misc@{ub}).



@endnode

@node Introduction "Neptune Documentation - Introduction"


   @{b}Introduction@{ub}


   It's the same old story: after looking for years for a @{i}really@{ui}
 good astrology program for the Amiga (or the PC !?!), I've decided to
 write one. By saying 'good' I don't mean a program only capable of very
 precise calculations (there are plenty of them even for the PC ;),
 neither simply a device filled with tons of more or less useful options:
 what I was looking for was a program capable of completely substituting
 a hand-drawn horoscope, thus providing a very accurate - but above all
 intuitive - image of the zodiac, so that the reader could easily
 concentrate on the interpretation without spending too much time
 figuring out what a certain graphic output could really mean.

   Obviously, this point of view could easily be rejected by those who
 - more or less unaware of Astrology - give the maximum importance to the
 ability of a program to provide 'automatically' all the intepretations
 written in plain english: although in a future version of my program I
 plan to add them, they are meant solely as a quick reference or reminder
 because (at least with the actual computer generation) no program will be
 able to substituite the mind in the most difficult phase of interpreting
 an horoscope: the synthesis of all the single meanings in a global
 picture.

@endnode

@node Features "Neptune Documentation - Features"


   @{b}@{fg shine}Neptune@{fg text} offers the following features@{ub}:


 - Computing of @{i}Birth-Horoscope@{ui} and @{i}Transits' Analysis@{ui}.

 - A very @{i}intuitive drawing@{ui} of the Horoscope with clear Planets,
 Signs and Aspects.

 - @{i}Animated@{ui} Planets' images with @{i}astronomic feel@{ui}.

 - Use of both @{i}traditional@{ui} and @{i}simplified@{ui} symbolism.

 - @{i}Graphic Online Help@{ui} activated by simply clicking on a Planet
 or Sign.

 - @{i}Data Entry Online Help@{ui} activated by pressing the HELP key
 during data entry.

 - @{i}Aligning algorithm@{ui} automatically avoiding overlayed images of
 Planets.

 - @{i}Screen-@{ui} and @{i}Font-sensitivity@{ui}: full support for any
 resolution and @{"graphic board" LINK Gfxboard}.

 - @{i}Intelligent Data Entry Parser@{ui} allowing multiple ways of
 entering the same data (eg. Time @{b}08.30@{ub} could be entered as
 @{b}8:30@{ub} or @{b}8.3@{ub}, etc.).

 - @{i}Easy access@{ui} to all functions: no complicate parameters are
 needed, everything is achieved with a mouse click.

 - @{i}Artistic@{ui} drawing - and therefore printing - of the Horoscope:
 the output of this program - if compared with many others - can be
 defined @{i}pleasant to the eye@{ui}.

 - Full possibility to LOAD, SAVE and PRINT data (not in the @{i}DEMO
 Version@{ui}).

 - Although @{i}high-end@{ui} Amigas are fully supported, @{i}every@{ui}
 function will be available (but slower!) even on a 68000-based Amiga with
 OS2.x and 1 Mb Chip Memory.

 - Although recommended, this program does not require any @{i}hard disk@{ui}.

 - Full compatibility with @{b}UAE@{ub}, a Unix (Linux, Solaris, HPUX, etc.)
 Amiga Emulator written by Bernd Schmidt
 <crux@pool.informatik.rwth-aachen.de> and ported to DOS, Windows95,
 XFree86/OS2, Mac, BeBox, and NextStep.

@endnode

@node UAE "UAE"


 @{b}UAE@{ub} is a Unix (Linux, Solaris, HPUX, etc.)
 Amiga Emulator written by Bernd Schmidt
 <crux@pool.informatik.rwth-aachen.de> and ported to DOS, Windows95,
 XFree86/OS2, Mac, BeBox, and NextStep.


@endnode


@node Gfxboard "Graphic boards"


   @{b}Graphic Boards Problems@{ub}


   @{fg shine}Neptune@{fg text} has been reported to work @{i}almost@{ui}
 100% with the @{i}Picasso@{ui} Gfx Board, with the only restriction being
 the non usability of @{"Animations" LINK Animate}, which trash the screen.

@endnode

@node Requirements "Neptune Documentation - Requirements"


   @{b}Requirements@{ub}


   The minimum requirements to run @{fg shine}@{i}Neptune@{ui}@{fg text} are:


 - Any @{b}Amiga@{ub} with at least 1 Mb Chip Memory.

 - Amiga @{b}OS2.04@{ub} or later.

 - @{b}HBasic2.library@{ub} (included).

 - @{"Nami fonts" LINK Nami} (included).


   @{b}@{fg shine}Neptune has been successfully tested on the following configurations:@{fg text}@{ub}


   @{fg fill}Platform   Processor   MHz   RAM   OS     Special@{fg text}

@REM   Platform   Processor   MHz   RAM   OS     Special

   A1200      68020       14    2     3.0

   A1200      68020       28    6     3.0    Blizzard1220/4

   A1200      68030       50    18    3.0    Blizzard1230 IV

   A2000      68000       7.14  1     2.04

   A2000      68000       7.14  5     2.04

   PC         Pentium     100   32    Win95  @{"UAE" LINK UAE}

   PC         Pentium     166   16    Win95  @{"UAE" LINK UAE}

@endnode

@node Installation "Neptune Documentation - Installation"


   @{b}Installation@{ub}


   In order to get @{i}@{fg shine}Neptune@{fg text}@{ui} properly installed,
 you can use the supplied @{i}Installation Script@{ui}.
 If you prefer to install it manually (not suggested), do the following:


   makedir [DEV:]NEPTUNE

   assign Neptune: [DEV:]NEPTUNE

   makedir Neptune:Docs


 If you want to use NI or standard icons:

   copy icons/NI/Neptune.info to [DEV:]

   copy icons/NI/Neptune1.0.info to Neptune:

   copy icons/NI/Docs.info to Neptune:

   copy icons/NI/Neptune1.0.guide.info to Neptune:Docs


 If you want to use MWB icons:

   copy icons/MWB/Neptune.info to [DEV:]

   copy icons/MWB/Neptune1.0.info to Neptune:

   copy icons/MWB/Docs.info to Neptune:

   copy icons/MWB/Neptune1.0.guide.info to Neptune:Docs


   copy docs/Neptune1.0.guide to Neptune:Docs

   copy bin/Neptune1.0 TO Neptune:

   makedir fonts:nami

   copy fonts/nami.font to fonts:

   copy fonts/nami/7 TO fonts:nami

   copy libs/HBasic2.library TO libs:


   @{fg fill}NOTE:@{fg text}

   According to your preferences, you can use the @{"MagicWB" LINK MWB} or
 @{"NewIcons" LINK NEWICONS} icons (which will look like  Standard 4-Color
 Icons if you don't have NewIcons installed).

@endnode


